# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: earned-run-average
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The **2019 Major League Baseball season** began on March 20, while the regular season ended on September 29.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] It was the 150th anniversary of professional baseball, dating back to the 1869 foundation of the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The World Series began October 22 and ended October 30 with the Washington Nationals defeating the Houston Astros in seven games to win their first World Series championship.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The entire schedule was released on August 22, 2018.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The 90th Major League Baseball All-Star Game was held on July 9 at Progressive Field, home of the Cleveland Indians.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The American League won, 4–3, for its seventh straight victory.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This was the final season when anyone on the 40-man expanded roster could be used in games from September 1 through the end of the regular season (so-called September call-ups).
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] As has been the case since 2013, teams were scheduled to play 19 games against each division opponent for a total of 76 games, and six or seven games against each team from the other two divisions for a total of 66 games.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The primary inter-league match-ups were AL East vs NL West, AL Central vs NL East and AL West vs NL Central.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The season began on March 20 and 21 with the Oakland Athletics and the Seattle Mariners playing in Tokyo, Japan, at the Tokyo Dome.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Excluding international openers, March 28 was the earliest Opening Day in history.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The previous earliest date was March 29 of the 2018 season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The second annual Mexico Series of games featured four matchups during the season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Louis Cardinals and the Cincinnati Reds at Monterrey, Mexico's Estadio de Béisbol Monterrey on April 13 and 14.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The other series, also in Monterrey, featured two games between the Houston Astros and the Los Angeles Angels on May 4 and 5.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Kansas City Royals faced the Detroit Tigers at Charles Schwab Field Omaha in Omaha, Nebraska, on June 13 for the MLB in Omaha game, only two days before the College World Series.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This was the first MLB game played in the state of Nebraska.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The MLB London Series featured the New York Yankees and Boston Red Sox at London Stadium in London, on June 29 and 30 making it the first regular season series played in London, under a two-year commitment.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The MLB Little League Classic at Muncy Bank Ballpark at Historic Bowman Field in Williamsport, Pennsylvania, coinciding with the Little League World Series, returned to the schedule for the third straight year.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] It was played between the Chicago Cubs and Pittsburgh Pirates on August 18.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Spring training for the 2019 season began in late February and lasted through late March.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Teams began workouts and practice for spring training beginning in mid February.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Pitchers and catchers reported first, followed by position players a few days later.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Prior to the start of the regular season, each team played between 22 and 35 spring training games, beginning on February 22.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] There were several times during spring training where a team had two different squads playing different teams simultaneously.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] In addition to spring training games, teams occasionally played exhibition games with non-MLB teams, such as Minor League Baseball teams, independent teams, or college teams.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] These exhibition games were not counted in spring training standings.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Spring training ended on March 26, two days before the Opening Day.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On December 10, Major League Baseball announced its first-ever All-MLB team.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Players were selected through fan votes (50%) and votes from a panel of experts (50%).
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The winners were selected based on merit, with no set number of nominees per position and no distinction between leagues.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On November 16, 2018, the Miami Marlins unveiled a new logo, team colors, and uniform for 2019, as part of changes instituted by the team's new CEO Derek Jeter.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The new design replaces one used since their 2012 move to Marlins Park and rebranding from the Florida Marlins to the Miami Marlins, and utilizes shades of red, blue, black, and slate.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On January 29, 2018, Major League Baseball stated that the Cleveland Indians had agreed to stop using their "Chief Wahoo" logo—which has attracted controversy as a stereotype of Native Americans—on their uniforms in 2019, as it was deemed to be "no longer appropriate for on-field use".
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In order to maintain trademarks and prevent it from falling into the public domain, the logo will continue to be used on a limited amount of team merchandise.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] All 30 teams wore patches this year on the right sleeve commemorating MLB's 150th anniversary.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The patch was also featured on caps on Opening Day.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] To honor the 150th anniversary of the Cincinnati Red Stockings becoming the first professional baseball team, the Cincinnati Reds announced on November 5, 2018, that the team would wear fifteen throwback uniforms.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Pirates are continuing to wear 1979 "bumblebee" throwbacks on Sundays this season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The team wore mono-black uniforms July 20 as the 40th anniversary of the 1979 World Series-winning team was honored.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Pirates and Brewers wore Negro leagues throwbacks June 1 and 7.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Pirates wore uniforms of the Pittsburgh Crawfords and the Brewers wore the uniforms of the Milwaukee Bears.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Twins and Royals wore Negro leagues throwbacks June 23.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Paul Colored Gophers, and the Royals wore 1942 uniforms of the Kansas City Monarchs.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Mariners and Astros wore 1980s–1990s throwbacks June 29.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Royals and Nationals wore 1969 throwbacks July 6.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Nationals wore the 1969 throwbacks of the Montreal Expos.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Phillies wore mono-burgundy 1979 "Saturday Night Special" throwbacks July 27.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] They were only worn once, on May 27, 1979.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Braves wore 1979 throwbacks, as well.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Braves wore 1970's throwbacks August 1 to 4.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Mariners and Astros wore 1980s throwbacks August 2.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Orioles and Astros wore 1989 throwbacks August 9.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Angels wore 1970s California Angels throwbacks August 16.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This was the Texas Rangers' final season at Globe Life Park in Arlington (formerly known as the Ballpark in Arlington and Ameriquest Field), where the team played its final regular season home game with a 6–1 win over the New York Yankees on September 29 before moving to Globe Life Field in 2020.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The stadium of the Seattle Mariners was renamed T-Mobile Park for the mobile provider (including its magenta-pink logo color as part of the park's branding atmosphere), after Safeco's contract with the team to call the venue Safeco Field expired at the end of the 2018 season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The home field of the San Francisco Giants had its fourth name in its history since opening in 2000, but its first name outside the same company, as Oracle will pay an unknown but significant amount for a twenty-year agreement to rename the former AT&T Park as Oracle Park.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] It also keeps Oracle's name on a Bay Area sports venue, as the Golden State Warriors left Oakland's Oracle Arena for the Chase Center .75 miles (1.2 km) south of Oracle Park at the end of the 2018–19 NBA season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This was the sixth year of the current eight-year deals with Fox Sports, ESPN, and TBS.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox aired eight weeks of baseball on Saturday Nights which led up to the 2019 Major League Baseball All-Star Game which also aired on Fox.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox then televised Saturday afternoon games for the final four weeks of the season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] FS1 televised games on Tuesday and on Saturday both during the afternoon and night.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN televised games on its flagship telecast *Sunday Night Baseball* as well as Monday and Wednesday nights.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS televised Sunday afternoon games for the last 13 weeks of the regular season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox and ESPN Sunday Night Baseball telecasts were exclusive; all other national telecasts were subject to local blackout.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS televised the National League Wild Card Game, Division Series, and the Championship Series.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN televised the American League Wild Card.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] FS1 and MLB Network televised the American League Division Series.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox and FS1 televised the American League Championship Series.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The World Series will air exclusively on Fox for the 20th consecutive year.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On April 30, 2019, Major League Baseball and YouTube agreed to a partnership for 13 exclusive baseball games.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The agreement was essentially a replacement to an earlier deal with Facebook Watch, which was criticized for requiring a Facebook account to access and for having too clunky of an interface.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The YouTube games would feature a pre and post game show, alongside the game, all produced by MLB Network.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] There was no requirement for a YouTube account to access the game.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The first game aired was between the Phillies and the Dodgers on July 18, 2019.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] After the season, MLB said they averaged 130,000 viewers per telecast.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The August 7, Dodgers-Cardinals telecast saw the highest peak of 320,000 live viewers.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Department of Justice regarding Disney's acquisition of 21st Century Fox, the Fox Sports Regional Networks were required to be sold off to third parties by June 18, 2019.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox also invoked a clause to give Yankee Global Enterprises the rights to buy their stake back in the YES Network.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Including YES, the Fox Sports Regional Networks broadcast games for 15 of the 30 MLB teams.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On March 8, YES was sold to a consortium including Yankee Global Enterprises, Amazon, and Sinclair Broadcast Group for $3.5 billion.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Then on May 3, Sinclair and Entertainment Studios agreed to purchase the rest of the Fox Sports Regional Networks.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The networks continued to use the Fox Sports branding for the rest of the regular season under a transitional license agreement.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WGN-TV broadcasts of Chicago Cubs and White Sox games concluded at the end of the season.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WGN held the local broadcast television rights of both teams since 1948.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The network's final telecasts took place on September 28 (Cubs) and September 29 (White Sox).
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Effective with the 2020 season, Cubs games will move exclusively to the new Marquee Sports Network, while White Sox games will air full-time on NBC Sports Chicago.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] MLB's contract with Facebook Watch has been further downsized, now only consisting of six games (reduced from 25).
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In addition, the games will no longer be exclusive to the service, and subject to blackout in-market.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The league also reached a new digital partnership with the streaming service DAZN, who now airs a daily studio program, *ChangeUp*, which features live look-ins on games in progress.
[src:earned-run-average/2019-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In mid-July, MLB and Google announced that 13 games will air exclusively on YouTube, produced by MLB Network.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss was born and raised in Wisconsin, where he attended St.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Mary's College (later part of Wyalusing Academy) in Prairie du Chien and the University of Wisconsin.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Mary's and then played in a semipro league where he caught the attention of Connie Mack.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss did not sign with Mack's team, but he attracted further major league interest after winning 19 games in 1900 for the Toledo Mud Hens.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss had another strong season for Toledo in 1901.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] After an offseason contract dispute between Joss, Toledo and Cleveland, he debuted with the Cleveland club in April 1902.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss led the league in shutouts that year.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] By 1905, Joss had completed the first of his four consecutive 20-win seasons.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Off the field, Joss worked as a newspaper sportswriter from 1906 until his death.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In 1908, he pitched a perfect game during a tight pennant race that saw Cleveland finish a half-game out of first place; it was the closest that Joss came to a World Series berth.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The 1910 season was his last, and Joss missed most of the year due to injury.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In April 1911, Joss became ill and he died the same month due to tuberculous meningitis.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He finished his career with 160 wins, 234 complete games, 45 shutouts and 920 strikeouts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Addie Joss was born on April 12, 1880, in Woodland, Dodge County, Wisconsin.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] His parents Jacob and Theresa (née Staudenmeyer) were farmers; his father, a cheesemaker who was involved in local politics, had emigrated from Switzerland.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] A heavy drinker of alcohol, he died from liver complications in 1890, when Joss was 10 years old; Joss remained sober throughout his life as a result of his father's death.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss attended elementary school in Juneau and Portage and high school at Wayland Academy in Beaver Dam, Wisconsin.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] By age 16 he finished high school and began teaching himself.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He was offered a scholarship to attend St.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Mary's College (also known as Sacred Heart College) in Watertown, where he played on the school's baseball team.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He also attended the University of Wisconsin (now University of Wisconsin–Madison), where he studied engineering.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Officials in Watertown were impressed with the quality of play of St.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Mary's and put the team on a semipro circuit.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] During his time on the semipro circuit, Joss employed his unique pitching windup, which involved hiding the ball until the very last moment in his delivery.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Connie Mack also sent a scout to watch Joss and later offered the young pitcher a job playing on his Albany club in the Western League, which Joss declined.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In 1899, Joss played for a team in Oshkosh, earning $10 per week ($387 in today's dollars).
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] After player salaries were frozen by team owners, Joss joined the junior team in Manitowoc, which had been split into two teams, as a second baseman and was soon promoted to the senior squad, where he was developed into a pitcher.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He was seen by a scout for the Toledo Mud Hens and in 1900 accepted a position with the team for $75 per month ($2,903).
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] While in Ohio he was considered "the best amateur pitcher in the state." He started the Mud Hens' season opener on April 28 and earned the win in the team's 16–8 victory.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Midway through the 1901 season, the Boston Americans of the upstart American League offered $1,500 ($58,050) to Toledo to buy out Joss's contract.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Louis Cardinals of the National League (NL) matched Boston's offer; Toledo rejected both offers.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss continued to pitch for the Mud Hens and by the end of the 1901 season he had won 27 games and had 216 strikeouts (some sources say 25 games).
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] After the season ended, Joss returned to Wisconsin where he led Racine to the 1901 Wisconsin baseball state championship against Rube Waddell's Kenosha squad.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He also enrolled at Beloit College and played American football.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] It was reported that Joss had signed with the Brooklyn Dodgers of the National League as early as August 18 and received a $400 advance ($15,480), but Joss denied receiving any money.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Mud Hens owner Charles Stroebel stated that he had signed Joss and other Mud Hens players for the 1902 season on August 12 and that the Western League was under the protection of the National League through September 1901.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Before 1901 ended, the Cleveland Bronchos offered $500 ($19,350) to Toledo in exchange for Joss and manager Bob Gilks, who would be a scout for Cleveland.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Toledo and Joss agreed and Joss was now a member of the American League, which was paying a premium on baseball talent to rival the National League.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Dodgers owner Charles Ebbets invited Joss for a meeting, which Joss declined, and Joss let it be known that he had told Stroebel he would play for the Mud Hens for the 1902 season, and received a $150 ($5,582) advance in February 1902.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In March 1902, Joss signed with Cleveland.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] For not returning the entire advance, Joss was charged with a felony and Stroebel pursued legal action.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Bronchos on April 26, and two days later he arrived in Toledo to turn himself in, accompanied by Bronchos majority owner Charles Somers, who was also American League vice president.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Stroebel also filed a civil suit against the Bronchos, stating that his business had been interfered with, but Stroebel agreed to withdraw his charges in July when he accepted Bronchos pitcher Jack Lundbom.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Cleveland Bronchos (also known as the Bluebirds) against the St.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The Browns' Jesse Burkett hit a shallow pop fly in the direction of right fielder Zaza Harvey.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Home plate umpire Bob Caruthers ruled that Harvey did not make a clean catch, so Burkett was credited with a hit.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] (Harvey and witnesses said the ball never hit the ground.) Joss finished his major league debut with a one-hitter.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss compiled a 17–13 record and 2.77 ERA during his major league rookie season.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He led the American League with five shutouts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] On October 11, 1902, Joss married Lillian Shinivar in Monroe, Michigan.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Shinivar was in attendance when Joss made his professional debut with the Mud Hens in 1900.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The couple had a son, Norman, and a daughter, Ruth.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Following the conclusion of the 1902 season, Joss was selected to the All-Americans, an all-star team from the American League who played exhibition games against their counterparts from the National League.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] To begin the 1903 season, the Cleveland organization changed the team's name to the "Naps" in honor of second baseman Nap Lajoie.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In Joss' second year, he went 18–13 and lowered his ERA from the season before to 2.19.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] His walks plus hits per inning pitched (WHIP) was an MLB-low 0.948.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] For the 1904 season, the 24-year-old Joss went 14–10 with a 1.59 ERA and did not give up a home run during the season.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Illness during the season reduced his starts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He had his first of four 20-win seasons in 1905 as he ended the season with a 20–12 record and 2.01 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He finished with a career-high 132 strikeouts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In 1906 his 1.72 ERA was third in the league and he finished with a 21–9 record and tied a career-high with nine shutouts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] To begin the 1907 season, Joss won his first 10 starts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He threw two one-hitters during the season, the first on September 4 against the Detroit Tigers and the second on September 25 versus the New York Highlanders.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] When teammate Heinie Berger threw his own one-hitter on September 26, it marked just the second time since 1900 that two pitchers from the same team had thrown back-to-back one-hitters.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss finished the season with career-bests in wins (finished 27–11) and 338+2⁄3 innings pitched.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] His win total tied with Doc White for highest in the American League and his WHIP was second-best (behind Cy Young) while both his complete game (34) and shutout (6) totals were third-best in the league.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Before the 1908 season started, the Naps' home field, League Park, was expanded by about 4,000 seats.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In what proved to be one of the tightest ever pitching duels in a perfect game, Joss took the mound for the Naps, while the White Sox pitcher was future Hall of Famer Ed Walsh.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Neither pitcher would give up an earned run in the 1–0 game.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Walsh, blistering through his own 39 win season, struck out 15 batters, gave up only one base on balls and allowed only four scattered hits by the Naps.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The Naps' Joe Birmingham scored the team's only run, which came in the third inning—the lone, unearned run scored as a result of a botched pickoff play and a wild pitch.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The tension in the ballpark was described by one writer as "a mouse working his way along the grandstand floor would have sounded like a shovel scraping over concrete." Joss, having faced the minimum 24 batters in the first eight innings, retired the first two batters in the top of the ninth.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss then faced White Sox pinch hitter John Anderson.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Anderson hit a line drive that could have resulted in a double had it not gone foul.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He then hit a ball to Naps third baseman Bill Bradley, which Bradley bobbled before throwing to first baseman George Stovall.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Stovall dug the ball out of the dirt to achieve the final out.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] With the win, Joss recorded the second ever perfect game in MLB's modern era.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He accomplished the feat with just 74 pitches, the lowest known pitch count ever achieved in a perfect game.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] After the game, Joss said, "I never could have done it without Larry Lajoie's and Stovall's fielding and without Birmingham's base running.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] For the season, Joss averaged 0.83 walks per nine innings, becoming one of 29 pitchers in MLB history to average less than one walk per nine innings.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] His season-ending WHIP of .806 is the fifth-lowest single-season mark in MLB history.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The Naps finished with a 90–64 record, a half-game behind Detroit.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] It was the closest Joss ever got to a World Series appearance.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] After amassing four consecutive 20-win seasons, Joss struggled in 1909 as a result of fatigue; by September he was shut down for the season.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss finished the year with a 14–13 record in 242+2⁄3 innings pitched and recorded a 1.71 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He finished fourth in the American League in ERA and third in WHIP (.944).
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss pitched a second no-hitter, on April 20, 1910, against the White Sox, becoming the first pitcher in MLB history to no-hit the same team twice, a feat not matched until Tim Lincecum of the San Francisco Giants no-hit the San Diego Padres in both 2013 and 2014.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In the second inning, the White Sox' Freddy Parent hit a ball toward third base.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Bill Bradley failed to field the ball cleanly and thus his throw to first base was not in time to get Parent out.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The initial ruling on the field was a base hit but it was later changed to an error.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss gave up two walks and recorded 10 assists.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He made just 13 appearances that season due to a torn ligament in his right elbow.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss made his last appearance of the season on July 25, and left the game in the fifth inning due to arm soreness.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In his final game, he allowed three runs on five hits and two walks with six strikeouts in a 4–0 loss.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In his final major league season, Joss finished with a 5–5 record in 107+1⁄3 innings.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] This marked the fifth time in Joss' nine years that the franchise finished with a losing record.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Of Joss' 160 major league wins, 45 were shutouts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss' 1.89 career ERA is ranked second all-time (to Ed Walsh), while his 0.97 WHIP (walks and hits per inning pitched) is the lowest career WHIP in MLB history.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He finished with a 160–97 record, 234 complete games, and 920 strikeouts.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss' repertoire included a fastball, a "slow ball" (today known as a changeup), and an "extremely effective" curve.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Baseball historians Rob Neyer and Bill James ranked Joss' fastball third (1900–1904) and sixth (1905–1909) in the major leagues.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] George Moriarty explained that Joss had only one curveball because "he believed that with a few well mastered deliveries he could acquire great control and success with less strain on his arm." In an era filled with spitball pitchers, Joss achieved his success without ever altering the baseball.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Illness and injury accompanied Joss throughout much of his professional career.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In 1903, a high fever forced him to miss the last month of the season.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He contracted malaria in April 1904 and then missed several starts with a back injury in 1905.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss was concerned about supporting his family after his baseball career ended; many players of the day had little education and few marketable job skills beyond their abilities on the diamond.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] As sportswriter Franklin Lewis wrote, "Only a handful of players in the rough, stirring, early days of the major leagues arrived from campuses.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] And when they did, sometimes the shock was too great for them.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Some grizzled holdovers from the 1890s were around and they bore down heavily on the eardrums of the so-called college-boy set." Joss was hired as a sports columnist after the 1906 season for the *Toledo News-Bee*.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He also served as their Sunday sports editor.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] His writings proved so popular that sales of the paper increased and a special phone line was installed in his office to field the large volume of calls he received from fans.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The increased popularity gave him an advantage when negotiating with the Naps before the 1907 season, and the club agreed to pay him $4,000 (equivalent to $138,000 in 2025).
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He later also wrote for the *Cleveland Press* and covered the World Series for the *News-Bee* and *Press* from 1907 to 1909.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The *Press* introduced Joss in columns this way: "Of all the baseball players in the land, Addie Joss is far and away the best qualified for this work.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] During the 1908–1909 offseasons, Joss worked on designing an electric scoreboard that would later be known as the Joss Indicator.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The Naps decided to install the scoreboard, which allowed spectators to monitor balls and strikes at League Park.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss attended spring training with Cleveland before the start of the 1911 season.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He collapsed on the field from heat prostration on April 3 in an exhibition game in Chattanooga, Tennessee.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He was taken to a local hospital and released the next day.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] As early as April 7, press reports had taken note of his ill health, but speculated about "ptomaine poisoning" or "nervous indigestion." The Naps traveled to Toledo for exhibition games on April 10 and Joss went to his home on Fulton Street where he was seen by his personal physician, Dr.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Chapman thought Joss could be suffering from nervous indigestion or food poisoning.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] By April 9, as Joss was coughing more and had a severe headache, Chapman changed his diagnosis to pleurisy and reported that Joss would not be able to play for one month and would need ten days of rest to recover.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss could not stand on his own and his speech was slurred.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss was well-liked by his peers and baseball fans.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Upon hearing of his death, the *Press* wrote "every train brings flowers" and "floral tributes by the wagonload are hourly arriving at the Joss home from all sections of the country." His family arranged for the funeral to take place on April 17.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] On that day, the Naps were to face the Detroit Tigers.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Naps players signed a petition stating that they would not attend the game so they could instead attend the funeral.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] They asked for the game to be rescheduled, but the Tigers balked at the request.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] American League president Ban Johnson initially supported the Tigers' position, but he ultimately sided with the Naps.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Naps owner Charles Somers and 15 Naps players attended the funeral, which was officiated by player-turned-evangelist Billy Sunday.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The first "all-star" game was played as a benefit for Joss's family on July 24, 1911.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The Naps invited players from the other seven American League teams to play against them.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Visiting club players who were involved in the game included Home Run Baker, Ty Cobb, Eddie Collins, Sam Crawford, Walter Johnson, Tris Speaker, Gabby Street, and Smoky Joe Wood.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] "I'll do anything they want for Addie Joss' family", Johnson said.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Washington Senators manager Jimmy McAleer volunteered to manage the all-stars.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] "The memory of Addie Joss is sacred to everyone with whom he ever came in contact.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The man never wore a uniform who was a greater credit to the sport than he", McAleer said.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] The game was attended by approximately 15,270 fans and raised nearly $13,000 ($449,000 today) to help Joss' family members pay remaining medical bills.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] In 1981, Lawrence Ritter and Donald Honig included him in their book *The 100 Greatest Baseball Players of All Time.* They described what they called "the Smoky Joe Wood Syndrome", where a player of truly exceptional talent has a career curtailed by injury or illness.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] They argued that such a player should still be included among the greatest all-time players, in spite of career statistics that would not quantitatively rank him with the all-time greats.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] They believed that Joss' career ERA was proof enough of his greatness to be included.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] Joss was inducted into the Cleveland Guardians Hall of Fame on July 29, 2006.
[src:earned-run-average/addie-joss] He was inducted in the same class as Ray Chapman, Rocky Colavito, Al López, Sam McDowell, Al Rosen and Herb Score.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Where ERA is the pitcher's ERA, lgERA is the average ERA of the league, and PF is the park factor of the pitcher in question.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] The average ERA+ is set to be 100; a score above 100 indicates that the pitcher performed better than average, while below 100 indicates worse than average.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] For instance, imagine the average ERA in the league is 4.00: if pitcher A has an ERA of 4.00 but is pitching in a ballpark that favors hitters, his ERA+ will be over 100.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Likewise, if pitcher B has an ERA of 4.00 but pitches in a ballpark favoring pitchers, then his ERA+ will be below 100.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] As a result, ERA+ can be used to compare pitchers across different run environments.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] In the above example, while ERA will lead one to believe that both pitchers pitched at the same level due to their ERAs being equivalent, ERA+ indicates that pitcher A performed better than pitcher B.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] ERA+ can thus be used to neutralize the effects of some well-known advantages and disadvantages on pitchers' ERA scores.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Pedro Martínez holds the modern record for highest ERA+ in a single season; he posted a 1.74 ERA in the 2000 season while pitching in the American League, which had an average ERA of 4.92, which gave Martínez an ERA+ of 291.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] While Bob Gibson has the lowest ERA in modern times (1.12 in the National League in 1968), the average ERA was 2.99 that year (the so-called Year of the Pitcher) and so Gibson's ERA+ is 258, eighth highest since 1900.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] 1968 was the last year that Major League Baseball employed the use of a pitcher's mound at 15 inches (380 mm); after that season it was lowered to 10 inches (250 mm).
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] The career record for ERA+ (with a minimum of 1,000 innings pitched) is held by Mariano Rivera, a closer whose career ERA+ is 205.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Upon retirement in 2013, with an ERA+ of 194 in his final season, Rivera's career record of 205 surpassed the record among retired players of 154, held by Martínez, bumping Jim Devlin, a pitcher in the 1870s, to third with 151.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Roger Clemens topped a 200 ERA+ three times, and Greg Maddux had two such seasons.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Players in **bold** are active as of the end of the 2020 season and have not announced their retirement.
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Single-season leaders include only pitchers eligible for the ERA title (a pitcher must throw a minimum of one inning per game scheduled for his team during the season to qualify for the ERA title).
[src:earned-run-average/adjusted-era] Only pitchers with 1,000 or more innings pitched are shown in the career leader list.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:earned-run-average/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith was born on August 6, 1945, in Toms River, New Jersey.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] At the age of five his family moved to Orange County, California.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He attended Woodrow Wilson High School in Long Beach, but transferred to Western High School in Anaheim from which he graduated.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1963, as a senior, the 6 ft tall (1.83 m) Messersmith had a 14–1 regular season won–loss record as a pitcher for Western's baseball team, a 0.75 earned run average (ERA), and a .344 batting average as a hitter.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] This was the only year he played primarily as a pitcher in high school.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He ended the 1963 season 15–2 or 16–2 overall, losing in a close championship game.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He had two no-hitters and a 17-strike out game.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Western came in second the 1963 California Interscholastic Federation (CIF) AAA playoffs, and Messersmith was named first-team All-CIF as a pitcher and Sunset League Player of the Year.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was unanimously selected as the Orange County Player of the Year by the Orange County Sportswriters.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was also the school's quarterback in football, but did not play as a senior due to injury.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith originally wanted to attend the University of Southern California (USC), but the school only offered him half of a scholarship to play baseball.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He received full scholarship offers from the University of California, Berkeley (Cal) and the University of California at Los Angeles (UCLA) and chose Cal.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1965 as a Cal sophomore, he had an 8–2 record, while leading the California Intercollegiate Baseball Association (CIBA) with a 1.63 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was unanimously selected to the 1965 CIBA All-Star Team, and was named an All-American.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He wanted a $50,000 signing bonus from any team that was asking him to leave college in 1965.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The Detroit Tigers and/or Boston Red Sox drafted him in 1965, but he returned to play at Cal for another year.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He had an 8–5 record in his junior year.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Overall at Cal, he had a 16–7 record with a 2.00 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Following his junior year of college, the California Angels drafted Messersmith with the 12th overall pick in the June 1966 secondary amateur draft for players previously drafted but not signed within six months.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] That same month Roland Hemond, head of the Angels' farm system, signed Messersmith for approximately $65,000.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1966, the Angels assigned Messersmith to the Triple-A Seattle Angels of the Pacific Coast League (PCL).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He started 12 of the 18 games in which he pitched, with a 4–6 record and 3.36 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1967, he was sent down to the Double-A El Paso Sun Kings of the Texas League, where he started 18 games, with a 9–7 record and 4.34 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1968, he played part of the season in Seattle again, starting 11 games with nine appearances as a relief pitcher, and going 6–7 with a 2.96 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith appeared in 28 games for the Angels in 1968, starting five.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He had a 4–2 record, three saves and a 2.21 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In his September 6, 1968 debut as a starting pitcher, against 1967 Cy Young Award winner Jim Lonborg, Messersmith pitched at two-hit shutout, winning the game 4–0 against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith pitched a full season with the Angels in 1969.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He started 33 games, with a 16–11 record, a 2.52 ERA, and 211 strikeouts in 250 innings pitched, with 100 bases on balls.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He did this on a team that was 71–91, fifth worst in the American League (AL).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He led all major league pitchers in least hits per nine innings pitched (6.084), had the AL's fourth best ERA among starting pitchers, fifth best WAR (wins above replacement) for pitchers (5.3), and third best strikeouts per nine innings pitched (7.596).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1970, he was 11–10 with a 3.01 ERA, and led the AL in hits per nine innings (6.658).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1971, Messersmith had his best year with the Angels.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Once again the Angels were a below average team, with a 76–86 record (.469 winning percentage), 25.5 games behind the Western Division champion Oakland Athletics.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith, however, had a 20–13 record (.606 winning percentage) in 38 starts, with a 2.99 ERA in 276.2 innings pitched, four shutouts, and 14 complete games.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was selected to the AL All-Star Team for the first time, and was fifth in voting for the Cy Young Award.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In 1972, Messersmith had physical problems with his right index finger (on his pitching hand), that required in-season surgery.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He missed nearly two months of play, and started only 21 games on the year.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] His record fell to 8–11 in 169.2 innings pitched, while his ERA improved to 2.81.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The Angels had another mediocre year (75–80).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In November 1972, the Angels traded Messersmith and infielder Ken McMullen to the Los Angeles Dodgers for five players - Frank Robinson, Bill Singer, Billy Grabarkewitz, Bobby Valentine, and Mike Strahler.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] In his five years with the Angels, Messersmith was 59–47 with a 2.78 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] During those five years, the Angels only had one winning season (86–76 in 1970).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith joined a strong Dodger rotation in 1973 that included, among others, future Hall of Fame pitcher Don Sutton (18–10), Claude Osteen (16–11) and Tommy John (16–7).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The team had a 95–66 record (second place in the National League (NL) Western Division), and Messersmith finished the season with a 14–10 record and 2.70 ERA in 33 starts.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He shined in 1974, finishing with 20 wins and 6 losses and a 2.59 ERA, on a Dodgers team that won the NL West with a 102–60 record.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was the NL's starting pitcher in the 1974 Major League Baseball All-Star Game.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He led the NL with 1.098 WHIP (walks plus hits per inning pitched), tied for most wins, had the second best winning percentage and the fifth best ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith finished second in balloting for the Cy Young Award, which was won by his Dodger teammate, relief pitcher Mike Marshall.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was 16th in NL Most Valuable Player (MVP) voting.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He also won the Gold Glove Award for the best NL fielding pitcher in 1974.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith started and won Game 2 of the 1974 National League Championship Series (NLCS) against the Pittsburgh Pirates, giving up two runs in seven innings.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The Dodgers won the NLCS, and Messersmith was one of the main factors in the Dodgers' return to the World Series for the first time since 1966.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The Dodgers lost the 1974 World Series to the Oakland A's in five games.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith started Game 1, giving up only two earned runs, but the Dodgers lost 3–2.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The key hit was a double by opposing pitcher Ken Holtzman (while Messersmith himself had two base hits in the game).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The decisive play, however, was a throwing error by Dodgers' third baseman Ron Cey, that allowed the A's winning third run to score.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was also the losing pitcher in Game 4.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith pitched 1975 without a contract, subject only to MLB's reserve clause.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He had a 19–14 record, with a career best year in ERA, games played, games started, complete games, shutouts, and innings pitched.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He led the National League in games started (40), innings pitched (321.2), complete games (19), shutouts (7), and base hits per nine innings (6.8), finishing second best in ERA with 2.29 (behind Randy Jones's 2.24).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith won his second Gold Glove as the league's best-fielding pitcher.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He was again selected to the NL All-Star team, was tied for fifth in the NL Cy Young Award voting and tied for 24th in the NL most valuable player vote.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith is most famous for his role in the historic 1975 Seitz decision, which led to the downfall of Major League Baseball's reserve clause and ushered in the current era of free agency.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] It began when Messersmith went to spring training in 1975 and began negotiating his 1975 contract.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He asked for a no-trade clause, which the Dodgers refused.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He refused to sign any contract and played the year subject to MLB's one-year reserve clause, after which he intended to seek free agency.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith and Dave McNally were the only two players in 1975 playing on the one-year reserve clause in effect at the time.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] McNally's season ended early due to injuries and he returned home, intending to retire, but agreeing to players' union director Marvin Miller's request that he sign onto the Messersmith grievance in case Messersmith ended up signing a new deal with the Dodgers before the season ended.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] "It was less of an economic issue at the time than a fight for the right to have control over your own destiny", Messersmith told *The Sporting News*, looking back on his decision a decade later.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] "It was a matter of being tired of going in to negotiate a contract and hearing the owners say, 'OK, here's what you're getting.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith and McNally won their case before arbitrator Peter Seitz, who was fired by the owners the day afterward.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] McNally followed through on his intention to retire, but Messersmith signed a three-year, $1 million deal with the Atlanta Braves.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Among other things, then-Braves owner Ted Turner suggested the nickname "Channel" for Messersmith and jersey number 17, in order to promote the television station that aired Braves games.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] National League President Chub Feeney quickly nixed the idea, in part using the argument it could be construed as improper advertising.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The Braves were a last place team in 1976.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith was 11–11 with a 3.04 ERA, and again was selected to the All-Star team.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] However, he started 12 fewer games and pitched in over 100 less innings than the preceding season.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] He suffered an elbow injury in 1977, and started only 16 games, pitching only a little more than 100 innings, with a 5–4 record.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith struggled trying to live up to his new contract which was sold to the New York Yankees for $100,000 at the Winter Meetings on December 8, 1977.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith was injured early in the 1978 season with a shoulder separation, and played in only six games for the Yankees in 1978.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The Yankees released him after the 1978 season (November 6, 1978) and he signed with the Dodgers (February 7, 1979).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] The Dodgers gave Messersmith the very thing their first refusal drove him toward testing and defeating the old reserve system: a no-trade clause.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] But the injuries and stress had taken too much toll; Messersmith pitched in only 11 games for the Dodgers in 1979, going 2–4 with a 4.90 ERA, and retired after the Dodgers released him on August 28.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Over his 12-year major league career, Messersmith was 130–99, with a 2.86 ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] After pitching 321.2 innings in 1975, he pitched fewer than 395 total innings over the next four years, and had ongoing arm troubles.
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith's lifetime 2.861 ERA is the fifth lowest among full-time starting pitchers whose careers began after the advent of the live-ball era in 1920, behind only Clayton Kershaw (2.50), Whitey Ford (2.75), Sandy Koufax (2.76), and Jim Palmer (2.856).
[src:earned-run-average/andy-messersmith] Messersmith served two stints as a baseball coach at Cabrillo College, from 1986 to 1991 and from 2005 to 2007, when he retired at age 63.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:earned-run-average/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The **Atlanta Braves** are an American professional baseball team based in the Atlanta metropolitan area.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves compete in Major League Baseball (MLB) as a member club of the National League (NL) East Division.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The club was founded in Boston, Massachusetts, in 1871 as the **Boston Red Stockings**.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves are one of two remaining National League charter franchises that debuted in 1876 and are the oldest continuously operating professional sports franchise in North America.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The franchise was known by various names until it adopted the **Boston Braves** name in 1912.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] After 81 seasons and one World Series title in Boston, the club moved to Milwaukee, Wisconsin, in 1953.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] With a roster of Hall-of-Fame players such as Hank Aaron, Eddie Mathews, and Warren Spahn, the **Milwaukee Braves** won the World Series in 1957.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite the team's success, fan attendance declined.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The club's owners moved the team to Atlanta, Georgia, in 1966.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves did not find much success in Atlanta until 1991.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The club has won an MLB record 23 divisional titles, 18 National League pennants, and four World Series championships.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves are the only Major League Baseball franchise to have won the World Series in three different home cities.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Since moving to Atlanta in 1966, the Braves have an overall win–loss record of 4,926–4,547–8 (.520) through the end of 2025.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Cincinnati Red Stockings, formed in 1869, were the first openly all-professional baseball team but disbanded after the 1870 season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Manager Harry Wright and players moved to Boston, forming the *Boston Red Stockings*, a charter team in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NAPBBP).
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Led by the Wright brothers, Ross Barnes, and Al Spalding, they dominated the National Association, winning four of five championships.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The original Boston Red Stockings team and its successors can lay claim to being the oldest continuously playing franchise in American professional sports.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The club was known as the Boston Red Caps when they played the first National League game in 1876, winning against the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite a weaker roster in the league's first year, they rebounded to secure the 1877 and 1878 pennants.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Managed by Frank Selee, they were a dominant force in the 19th century, winning eight pennants.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] By 1898, the team was known as the Beaneaters and had won 102 games that season, with stars like Hugh Duffy, Tommy McCarthy, and "Slidin'" Billy Hamilton.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1901, the American League was introduced, causing many Beaneaters players including stars Duffy and Jimmy Collins to leave for clubs of the rival league.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team struggled, recording only one winning season from 1900 to 1913.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1907, they temporarily dropped the red color from their stockings due to infection concerns.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The club underwent various nickname changes until becoming the Braves before the 1912 season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Ward, named the club after the owner, James Gaffney.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Gaffney was called one of the "braves" of New York City's political machine, Tammany Hall, which used a Native American chief as its symbol.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1914, the Boston Braves experienced a remarkable turnaround in what would become one of the most memorable seasons in baseball history.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Starting with a dismal 4–18 record, the Braves found themselves in last place, trailing the league-leading New York Giants by 15 games after losing a doubleheader to the Brooklyn Robins on July 4.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] However, the team rebounded with an incredible hot streak, going 41–12 from July 6 to September 5.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] On August 3, Joseph Lannin, the president of the Red Sox, offered Fenway Park to the Braves free of charge for the remainder of the season as their usual home, the South End Grounds, was too small.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] On September 7 and 8, they defeated the Giants in two out of three games, propelling them into first place.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite being in last place as late as July 18, the Braves secured the pennant.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] They became the only team under the old eight-team league format to achieve this after being in last place on the Fourth of July.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] They were in last place as late as July 18, but were close to the pack, moving into fourth on July 21 and second place on August 12.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves entered the 1914 World Series led by captain and National League Most Valuable Player, Johnny Evers.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Boston club was a slight underdog against Connie Mack's Philadelphia A's.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] However, they swept the Athletics and won the world championship.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Inspired by their success, owner Gaffney constructed a modern park, Braves Field, which opened in August 1915.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] At the time it was the largest park in the majors, boasting 40,000 seats and convenient public transportation access.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] From 1917 to 1933, the Boston Braves struggled.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] After a series of different owners, a syndicate led by Emil Fuchs and including pitching great and Fuchs' longtime friend Christy Mathewson bought the team in 1923.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Mathewson's death in 1925 left Fuchs in control of the team.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite Fuchs' commitment to success, the team faced challenges overcoming the damage from previous years.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] It was not until 1933 and 1934, under manager Bill McKechnie, that the Braves became competitive, but the team's improvement in performance did little to help its finances.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In an effort to boost fan attendance and finances, Fuchs orchestrated a deal with the New York Yankees to acquire Babe Ruth in 1935.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Ruth was appointed team vice president with promises of profit shares and managerial prospects.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Initially, Ruth seemed to provide a spark on opening day, but his declining skills became evident.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Ruth's inability to run and poor fielding led to internal strife, and it became clear that his titles were symbolic.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Ruth retired on June 1, 1935, shortly after hitting his last three home runs.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves finished the season with a dismal 38–115 record, marking the franchise's worst season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Fuchs lost control of the team in August 1935, leading to a rebranding attempt as the Boston Bees, but it did little to alter the team's fortune.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Construction magnate Lou Perini took over, eventually restoring the Braves' name.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite World War II causing a brief setback, the team, led by pitcher Warren Spahn, enjoyed impressive seasons in 1946 and 1947 under Perini's ownership.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1948, the team won the pennant, behind the pitching of Spahn and Johnny Sain.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The poem reached and found favor with an audience so wide that the poem's sentiment, now usually paraphrased as "Spahn and Sain and pray for rain" or "Spahn and Sain, then pray for rain", entered the baseball vocabulary.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The 1948 World Series, which the Braves lost in six games to the Indians, turned out to be the Braves' last hurrah in Boston.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] On March 13, 1953, Perini announced the club's move to Milwaukee.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Perini cited the advent of television and the lack of fan enthusiasm for the Braves in Boston as the key factors in deciding to move the franchise.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Milwaukee Braves' move to Wisconsin for the 1953 season was an immediate success, as they drew a National League-record 1.8 million fans and finished the season second in the league.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Manager Charlie Grimm was named NL Manager of the Year.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Throughout the 1950s, the Braves were a National League power.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Driven by sluggers Eddie Mathews and Hank Aaron, the team won two pennants and finished second twice between 1956 and 1959.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1957, Aaron's MVP season led the Braves to their first pennant in nine years, followed by a World Series victory against the formidable New York Yankees.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite a strong start in the World Series rematch the following season, the Braves ultimately lost the last three games and the World Series.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The 1959 season ended in a tie with the Los Angeles Dodgers, who defeated the Braves in a playoff series.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The ensuing years saw fluctuating success, including the Braves finishing fifth in 1963, their first time in the "second division".
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1962, team owner Louis Perini sold the Braves to a Chicago-based group led by William Bartholomay.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Bartholomay intended to move the team to Atlanta in 1965, but legal hurdles kept them in Milwaukee for an extra season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] After arriving in Atlanta in 1966, the Braves found success in 1969, winning the first National League West Division title with the onset of divisional play.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In the National League Championship Series the Braves were swept by the "Miracle Mets".
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] They posted only two winning seasons between 1970 and 1981.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Fans in Atlanta had to be satisfied with the achievements of Hank Aaron, who by the end of the 1973 season, had hit 713 home runs, one short of Babe Ruth's record.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] On April 4, opening day of the next season, he hit No.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] 714 in Cincinnati, and on April 8, in front of his home fans and a national television audience, he finally beat Ruth's mark with a home run to left-center field off left-hander Al Downing of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Aaron spent most of his career as a Milwaukee and Atlanta Brave before being traded to the Milwaukee Brewers on November 2, 1974.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1976, the team was purchased by media magnate Ted Turner, owner of superstation WTBS, as a means to keep the team (and one of his main programming staples) in Atlanta.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Turner used the Braves as a major programming draw for his fledgling cable network, making the Braves the first franchise to have a nationwide audience and fan base.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] WTBS marketed the team as "The Atlanta Braves: America's Team", a nickname that still has some currency in certain areas of the country, especially the South.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The financially strapped Turner used money already paid to the team for their broadcast rights as a down-payment.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Turner quickly gained a reputation as a quirky, hands-on baseball owner.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] On May 11, 1977, Turner appointed himself manager.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] However, the MLB passed a rule in the 1950s barring managers from holding a financial stake in their teams, Turner was ordered to relinquish that position after one game (the Braves lost 2–1 to the Pittsburgh Pirates extending their losing streak to 17 games).
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves did not enjoy much success between 1978 and 1990.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] However, in the 1982 season, led by manager Joe Torre, the Braves secured their first divisional title since 1969.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team was led by standout performances from key players such as Dale Murphy, Bob Horner, Chris Chambliss, Phil Niekro, and Gene Garber.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves were swept in the NLCS in three games by the Cardinals.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Murphy won the National League's Most Valuable Player award in 1982 and 1983.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] From 1991 to 2005, the Atlanta Braves enjoyed a remarkable era of success in baseball, marked by a record-setting 14 consecutive division titles, five National League pennants, and a World Series championship in 1995.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Bobby Cox returned as manager in 1990, leading the team's turnaround after finishing the previous season with the worst record in baseball.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Notable developments included the drafting of Chipper Jones in 1990 and the hiring of general manager John Schuerholz from the Kansas City Royals.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves' remarkable journey began in 1991, known as the "Worst to First" season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Overcoming a shaky start, the Braves bounced back led by young pitchers Tom Glavine and John Smoltz.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team secured the NL pennant in a memorable playoff race, ultimately losing a closely contested World Series to the Minnesota Twins.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The following year, the Braves won the NLCS in dramatic fashion against the Pirates but fell short in the World Series against the Toronto Blue Jays.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1993, the Braves strengthened their pitching staff with the addition of Cy Young Award winner Greg Maddux in free agency.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite posting a franchise-best 104 wins, they lost in the NLCS to the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team moved to the Eastern Division in 1994, sparking a heated rivalry with the New York Mets.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The player's strike cut short the 1994 season just before the division championships, but the Braves rebounded in 1995, defeating the Cleveland Indians to win the World Series.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] With this World Series victory, the Braves became the first team in Major League Baseball to win world championships in three different cities.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves reached the World Series in 1996 and 1999 but were defeated both times by the New York Yankees.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1996, Time Warner acquired Ted Turner's Turner Broadcasting System, including the Braves.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite their continued success with a ninth consecutive division title in 2000, the Braves faced postseason disappointment, losing in a sweep to the St.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team won division titles from 2002 to 2004, but experienced early exits in the NLDS each year.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In December 2005, Time Warner put the club up for sale, leading to negotiations with Liberty Media.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] After over a year of talks, a deal was reached in February 2007 for Liberty Media to acquire the Braves for $450 million, a magazine publishing company, and $980 million in cash.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The sale, valued at approximately $1.48 billion, was contingent on approval from 75 percent of MLB owners and Commissioner Bud Selig.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Bobby Cox's final year as manager in 2010 saw the Braves return to the postseason for the first time since 2005.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team secured the NL Wild Card but fell to the San Francisco Giants in the National League Division Series in four closely contested games, marking the conclusion of Bobby Cox's managerial career.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The following season, the Braves suffered a historic September collapse to miss the postseason.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The club bounced back in 2012 and returned to the postseason in Chipper Jones' final season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves won 94 games in 2012, but that wasn't enough to win the NL East, so they faced the St.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Louis Cardinals in the inaugural Wild Card Game.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Chipper Jones's last game was a memorable one: the Braves lost the one-game playoff 6–3, but the game would be remembered for a controversial infield fly call that helped end a Braves rally in the 8th inning.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 2017, the Atlanta Braves began playing at Truist Park, replacing Turner Field as their home stadium.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Following an MLB investigation into international signing rule violations, general manager John Coppolella resigned and faced a baseball ban.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Alex Anthopoulos took over as the new general manager.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team's chairman, Terry McGuirk, apologized for the scandal and expressed confidence in Anthopoulos's integrity.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] A new on-field mascot named Blooper was introduced at a fan event before the 2017 season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Under Anthopoulos, the Braves made the playoffs in six of his first seven seasons.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 2020, the Braves reached the National League Championship Series, but ultimately lost to the Dodgers after leading 3–1.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In the 2021 season, the Braves won the National League East with an 88–73 record.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In the postseason, they quickly defeated the Milwaukee Brewers in the NL Division Series 3–1.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves again faced the Dodgers in the 2021 NLCS, and won in six games to take Atlanta's first National League pennant since 1999.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves advanced to the World Series.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] They defeated the Houston Astros in six games to win their fourth World Series title.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves failed to qualify for the postseason in 2025, ending a streak of seven consecutive appearances.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] After 49 years with the organization, including ten seasons as manager, the team announced that Snitker would step down from his managerial role and transition into an advisory position with the club.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In November 2025, the Braves announced that longtime bench coach Walt Weiss would be promoted to manager.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Weiss, a former All-Star shortstop also spent part of his playing career in Atlanta.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves logos have evolved over the years, featuring a Native American warrior from 1945 to 1955, followed by a laughing Native American with a mohawk and a feather from 1956 to 1965.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The modern logo, introduced in 1987, includes the cursive word "Braves" with a tomahawk below it.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Uniforms adopted that year evoked their 1950s classic look.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The City Connect uniform features "The A" across the chest, accompanied by a cap with the "A" logo and 1974 uniform colors.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves retired the '70s-era City Connects and unveiled a new alternate uniform ahead of the 2026 season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The new jersey is an homage to their cable television-fueled growth in the 1980s.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Powder-blue pullovers with a script "Atlanta" on the front and a lowercase "A" hat reference their contemporary away uniform, while an "ATL" wordmark on the left sleeve and printing above the laundry tag are designed similar to the classic TBS SuperStation logo.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Over the 120 years since the inception of the World Series (119 total World Series played), the Braves franchise has won a total of four World Series Championships.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves are the only franchise to have won a World Series in three different cities.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Boston Braves played at the South End Grounds from their inception.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] After a fire destroyed the park in 1894, the club temporarily played at the Congress Street Grounds until the South End Grounds could be rebuilt.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] During the 1914 season, it became evident that the South End Grounds was too small to accommodate larger crowds, prompting the team to play some games at Fenway Park.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] To address the need for a larger venue, Braves Field was built in 1915.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Braves Field remained the club's home in Boston until the team relocated to Milwaukee.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Milwaukee County Stadium was constructed in 1950 to attract a Major League Baseball team and became the Braves' new home in 1953.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team played there until moving to Atlanta in 1966.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The city of Atlanta constructed Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium in 1965 after reaching an agreement with the Braves to relocate from Milwaukee.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves played at Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium until 1997, when they moved to Turner Field.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Originally built as Centennial Olympic Stadium for the 1996 Summer Olympics, the venue was later converted into a ballpark for the Braves.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Turner Field served as the Braves' home ballpark through the 2016 season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Atlanta Braves home ballpark has been Truist Park since 2017.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Truist Park is located approximately 10 miles (16 km) northwest of downtown Atlanta in the unincorporated community of Cumberland, in Cobb County, Georgia.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves opened Truist Park on April 14, 2017, with a four-game sweep of the San Diego Padres.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The park received positive reviews from critics.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Woody Studenmund of the Hardball Times called the park a "gem" saying that he was impressed with "the compact beauty of the stadium and its exciting approach to combining baseball, business and social activities." J.J.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Since 2019, the Braves have played spring training games at CoolToday Park in North Port, Florida.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The ballpark opened on March 24, 2019, with the Braves' 4–2 win over the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves left Champion Stadium, their previous Spring Training home, near Orlando, to reduce travel times and to get closer to other teams' facilities.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] CoolToday Park also serves as the Braves' year-round rehabilitation facility.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Although their first major confrontation occurred when the Mets swept the Braves in the 1969 National League Championship Series (NLCS), the rivalry did not become especially heated until the 1994 season when division realignment put both the Mets and the Braves in the National League East division.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves faced the Mets in the 1999 National League Championship Series.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves initially took a 3–0 series lead, seemingly on the verge of a sweep, but the Mets rallied in Game 4 and Game 5.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite the Mets' resilience, the Braves eventually won the series in Game 6 with Andruw Jones securing a dramatic walk-off walk, earning their 5th National League pennant of the 1990s.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 2022, the Braves and Mets both finished with 101 wins.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The National League East title and a first-round bye came down to a crucial three-game series at Truist Park from September 30 to October 2.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Mets entered with a slight lead but faltered as the Braves swept the series, clinching the division title and first-round playoff bye.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Since the Mets joined the league in 1962, both teams have won two World Series titles.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves have captured six NL pennants, while the Mets have won five.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves hold the advantage in the all-time head-to-head record between the two teams at 516–425.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] However, the Mets have the upper hand in playoff matchups with a 5–4 record.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In addition to having strong fan support in the Metro Atlanta area and the state of Georgia, the Braves have been referred to as "America's Team" in reference to the team's games being broadcast nationally on TBS from the 1970s until 2007, giving the team a nationwide fan base.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves boast heavy support within the Southeastern United States particularly in states such as Mississippi, Alabama, South Carolina, North Carolina, Tennessee and Florida.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] In 1991, fans of the Atlanta Braves popularized the "tomahawk chop" during games.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The use of foam tomahawks faced criticism from Native American groups, who regarded it as demeaning.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Despite protests, the Braves' public relations director defended it as a "proud expression of unification and family." The controversy resurfaced in 2019 when Cherokee Nation member and St.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Louis Cardinals pitcher Ryan Helsley found the chop insulting, prompting the Braves to modify their in-game experience.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] During the off-season, discussions ensued with Native American representatives, and amid pressure in 2020 to change their name, the Braves announced ongoing talks about the chop but insisted the team name would remain unchanged.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The debate over the tomahawk chop continued into 2021.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] While some Native American leaders, like Richard Sneed, the Principal Chief of the Eastern Band of Cherokee Indians, expressed personal indifference or tolerance, acknowledging it as an acknowledgment of Native American strength, others vehemently opposed it.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Sneed emphasized larger issues facing Native American communities and questioned the focus on the chop.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Eastern Cherokee Band of Indians and the Braves initiated efforts to incorporate Cherokee language and culture into the team's activities, stadium, and merchandise, aiming for greater cultural sensitivity despite differing opinions within the Native American community.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Brian Snitker stepped down as manager of the Braves after the 2025 season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The team named Walt Weiss as his replacement.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Weiss had served as a coach with the Braves since 2018, and previously managed the Colorado Rockies from 2013 to 2016.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Braves players have won seven Most Valuable Player (MVP) awards, with Dale Murphy notably earning the honor in back-to-back years, 1982 and 1983.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Five Braves pitchers have received the Cy Young Award, given to the league's best pitcher, including Greg Maddux, who won it three consecutive times in 1993, 1994, and 1995.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Two Braves managers have been named Manager of the Year, with Bobby Cox winning the award three times, in 1991, 2004, and 2005.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Additionally, eight Braves players have been honored with the Rookie of the Year awards.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Braves have retired eleven numbers in the history of the franchise.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Most recently, Andruw Jones' number 25 was retired in 2023.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Other retired numbers include Chipper Jones' number 10, John Smoltz's number 29, Bobby Cox's number 6, Tom Glavine's number 47, and Greg Maddux's number 31.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Additionally, the Braves have retired Hank Aaron's number 44, Dale Murphy's number 3, Phil Niekro's number 35, Eddie Mathews' number 41, and Warren Spahn's number 21.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Jackie Robinson's number 42 is also retired across all of Major League Baseball, with the exception of Jackie Robinson Day.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Six of the eleven numbers (Cox, Chipper Jones, Andruw Jones, Smoltz, Maddux, and Glavine) were on the Braves at the same time.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Of the eleven Braves whose numbers have been retired, all who are eligible for the National Baseball Hall of Fame have been elected, with the exception of Dale Murphy.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The color and design of the retired numbers on commemorative markers and other in-stadium signage reflect the primary uniform design at the time the player was on the team.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The Atlanta Braves farm system consists of six minor league affiliates.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] As of the 2026 season, the Atlanta Braves' regional rights will be held in-house by the team under the banner BravesVision.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Games will be distributed via partnerships with television providers in the team's market, as well as via a direct-to-consumer streaming service operated by MLB Local Media.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Selected games are carried by a network of Gray Media television stations, led by WPCH-TV (the former WTBS).
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Gray produces a package of spring training games, and carrying a package of regular season games in simulcast with BravesVision.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Brandon Gaudin serves as the play-by-play announcer and C.J.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Jeff Francoeur and Tom Glavine will also join the broadcast for a few games during the season.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Peter Moylan, Nick Green, and John Smoltz also appear in the booth for select games as in-game analysts.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The radio broadcast team is led by the tandem of play-by-play announcer Ben Ingram and analyst Joe Simpson.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] Braves games are broadcast across Georgia and seven other states on at least 172 radio affiliates, including flagship station 680 The Fan in Atlanta and stations as far away as Richmond, Virginia; Louisville, Kentucky; and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:earned-run-average/atlanta-braves] The games are carried on at least 82 radio stations in Georgia.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] In baseball statistics, **earned run average** (**ERA**) is the average of earned runs allowed by a pitcher per nine innings pitched (i.e. the traditional length of a game).
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] It is determined by dividing the number of earned runs allowed by the number of innings pitched and multiplying by nine.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Runs resulting from passed balls, defensive errors (including pitchers' defensive errors), and runners placed on base at the start of extra innings are recorded as unearned runs and omitted from ERA calculations.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Henry Chadwick is credited with devising the statistic, which caught on as a measure of pitching effectiveness after relief pitching came into vogue in the 1900s.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Prior to 1900 and for many years afterward, pitchers were routinely expected to pitch a complete game, and their win–loss record was considered sufficient in determining their effectiveness.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] After pitchers like James Otis Crandall and Charley Hall made names for themselves as relief specialists, gauging a pitcher's effectiveness became more difficult using the traditional method of tabulating wins and losses.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Some criterion was needed to capture the apportionment of earned-run responsibility for a pitcher in games that saw contributions from other pitchers for the same team.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Since pitchers have primary responsibility for getting opposing batters out, they must assume responsibility when a batter they do not retire at the plate moves to base, and eventually reaches home, scoring a run.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] A pitcher is assessed an **earned run** for each run scored by a batter (or the batter's pinch-runner) who reaches base while batting against that pitcher.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] The National League first tabulated official earned run average statistics in 1912 (the outcome was called "Heydler's statistic" for a while, after then-NL secretary John Heydler), and the American League later accepted this standard and began compiling ERA statistics.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Baseball encyclopedias will often display ERAs for earlier years, but these were computed retroactively.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Negro league pitchers are often rated by *RA*, or total runs allowed, since the statistics available for Negro league games did not always distinguish between earned and unearned runs.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] As with batting average, the definition of a good ERA varies from year to year.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] During the dead-ball era of the 1900s and 1910s, an ERA below 2.00 (two earned runs allowed per nine innings) was considered good.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] In the late 1920s and through the 1930s, when conditions of the game changed in a way that strongly favored hitters, a good ERA was below 4.00; only the highest caliber pitchers, for example Dazzy Vance or Lefty Grove, would consistently post an ERA under 3.00 during these years.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] In the 1960s, sub-2.00 ERAs returned as other influences, such as ballparks with different dimensions, were introduced.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Starting with the 2019 season, an ERA under 4.00 is again considered good.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] The single-season record for the lowest ERA is held by Dutch Leonard, who in 1914 had an earned run average of 0.96, pitching 224.2 innings with a win–loss record of 19–5.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] The all-time record for the lowest single season earned run average by a pitcher pitching 300 or more innings is 1.12, set by Bob Gibson in 1968.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] The record for the lowest career earned run average is 1.82, held by Ed Walsh, who played from 1904 through 1917.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Some players may be listed with infinite ERAs.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] This can happen if a pitcher allows one or more earned runs without retiring a batter.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Several players have registered an infinite ERA for their limited pitching careers in MLB, usually a single appearance.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Examples include Bill Ford with the Boston Bees in 1936 and Fred Bruckbauer with the Minnesota Twins in 1961.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Outfielder Vic Davalillo made two pitching appearances with St.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Louis Cardinals in 1969 and failed to record an out while facing four batters and allowing one run, leaving him with an infinite ERA as a major-league pitcher.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] (This comes from attempting to divide any non-zero number by zero).
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] An undefined ERA occasionally occurs at the beginning of a baseball season when a pitcher has yet to appear in any games.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] It is sometimes incorrectly displayed as zero or as the lowest-ranking ERA.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] At times it can be misleading to judge relief pitchers solely on ERA, because they are charged only for runs scored by batters who reached base while batting against them.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Thus, if a relief pitcher enters the game while his team is leading by 1 run, with 2 outs and the bases loaded, and then gives up a single which scores 2 runs, he is not charged with those runs.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] If he retires the next batter (and pitches no more innings), his ERA for that game will be 0.00 despite having surrendered the lead.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] (He is recorded with a blown save if those runs tied the game or affected a lead change.) Starting pitchers operate under the same rules, but are not called upon to start pitching with runners already on base.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] In addition, relief pitchers know beforehand that they will only be pitching for a relatively short while, allowing them to exert themselves more for each pitch, unlike starters who typically need to conserve their energy over the course of a game in case they are asked to pitch 7 or more innings.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] The reliever's freedom to use their maximum energy for a few innings, or even for just a few batters, helps them keep their ERAs down.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] ERA, taken by itself, can also be misleading when trying to objectively judge starting pitchers, though not to the extent seen with relief pitchers.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] The advent of the designated hitter rule in the American League in 1973 made the pitching environment significantly different.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Starting in 1997, when teams began playing teams from the other league during the regular season, the DH rule was in effect only when such interleague games are played in an American League park; this was rendered moot after the National League permanently adopted the DH in 2022.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] This difference between the leagues (the DH) also affected relievers, but not to the same degree.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] This is because National League relievers actually pitched to pitchers less often than NL starters did for a number of reasons, mainly because relievers are usually active in later innings when the double switch was available and/or pinch hitters tended to be used in the pitcher's batting spot.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] ERA is also affected somewhat by the ballpark where a pitcher's team plays half its games, as well as the tendency of hometown official scorers to assign errors instead of base hits in plays that could be either.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] As an extreme example, pitchers for the Colorado Rockies have historically faced many problems, all damaging to their ERAs.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] The combination of high altitude (5,280 ft or 1,610 m) and a semi-arid climate in Denver causes fly balls to travel up to 10% further than at sea level.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Denver's altitude and low humidity also diminish the ability of pitchers to throw effective breaking balls, due to both reduced air resistance and difficulty in gripping dry baseballs.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] These conditions have been countered to some extent since 2002 by the team's use of humidors to store baseballs before games.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] These difficult circumstances for Rockies pitchers may not adversely affect their win–loss records, since opposing pitchers must deal with the same problems.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Indeed, hometown hurlers have some advantage in any given game since they are physically acclimated to the altitude and often develop techniques to mitigate the challenges of this ballpark.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Still, conditions there tend to inflate Rockies' ERAs relative to the rest of the league.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] In modern baseball, sabermetrics uses several defense independent pitching statistics (DIPS) including a Defense-Independent ERA in an attempt to measure a pitcher's ability regardless of factors outside his control.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] For example, this is the premise of Nate Silver's forecasts of ERAs using his PECOTA system.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Silver also developed a "quick" earned run average (QuikERA or QERA) to calculate an ERA from peripheral statistics including strikeouts, walks, and groundball percentage.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Unlike peripheral ERA or PERA, it does not take into account park effects.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] Another statistic derived from ERA is Adjusted ERA, also called ERA+, which adjusts a pitcher's ERA to a scale where 100 is average for the league and takes into account the various dimensions and other factors of each ballpark.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] In baseball statistics, **runs per nine innings** (denoted by **R/9** or **RA9**) is a measure of a pitcher's effectiveness in preventing runs; calculated as: (9 × runs allowed) / (innings pitched).
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] In this way, it is different from the ERA in that all runs, rather than only earned runs, are included.
[src:earned-run-average/earned-run-average] This is a list of the lowest ERAs among pitchers that played their entire careers after 1920 (minimum 1,500 innings pitched, starting pitcher).
